Gary Danko has always been one of those really hyped up restaurants that everyone raves about. Now, I think maybe people are just raving about being able to SAY they ate at the infamous Gary Danko, because honestly, we were far from impressed. The service was what I expected for the prices we paid, and they did an excellent job making us feel special with our birthday and congratulatory desserts, but the rest of the food was just OK. I practically licked the sauce my oysters came in off the plate, and the soft shell crab was delicious, but everything else was passable. Maybe some dishes are better than others, but considering the prices and the time it takes to get a reservation and its reputation, every dish on that menu should be amazing! But what I find amazing (and unbelievable) now, are these scores of 5 star reviews - are we eating at the same restaurant?! Also, I'm a sucker for nice ambiance and decor, so I would personally justify higher prices for great atmosphere, but even the restaurant wasn't particularly nicer than any others I've been in.

If it weren't for the desserts, Danko would be a highly disappointing 3-star flop. If they had a dessert tasting like at Providence in Los Angeles, I'm all in. I could then skip dinner and just have dessert. The amuse of merguez lamb sausage with cous cous was average. It was a questionable choice to open the evening with a spicy merguez. The deep fried egg appetizer with white polenta, king trumpet mushrooms, croutons, chives, and frissee was a dish that inspired breakfast. The eggs were perfectly cooked and burst with egg yolk when pierced. This was the only savory dish that I enjoyed, but the kitchen let an herb stem in the food slip though. Another starter, the pistachio coated sweetbreads with potato puree, roasted cauliflower, and mache was unbalanced. The cauliflower and sweetbreads were a double-whammy of pungent items. The pistachio crust didn't create a flavorful or crunchy exterior. The sweetbreads were laced with connective membrane that was unattractive. Like the errant stem, this was another sign the kitchen is not paying attention to details For mains, the lemon pepper duck breast was nicely cooked, but lacked much flavor. The duck & potato hash, shaped into a round, arrived cold and lacked fun potato starchiness. The outer leaf of the cabbage was stiff instead of tender and should have been peeled off before serving. The parsnip and carrot was an afterthought that "seemed" like a standard garnish that is put on all plates. Another entrÃ©e was the branzini with fennel and potato puree, orange segments, and saffron-infused orange sauce. The branzini was well cooked but overly mild. The concept of the dish sounds inventive, but ended up tasting conventional. Now for the good part - the desserts. Thankfully, we ordered two desserts instead of sharing one. I had the warm Louisiana butter cake with apples, berries, and lemon honey. It was inviting with an ideal balance between sugary, rich, and fruity. The ice cream macaroon sandwiches came in three flavors - pecan, raspberry, and pineapple. They had a good balance between the sweet from the ice cream and the bitter from the egg white. Both desserts weren't fancy and stylish, but ultimately very satisfying. The petit fours were nine tiny cookies that were ideal nibbles with appealingly conservative flavors. Female diners were given a parting gift of pineapple and vanilla white breakfast cake. (Kinda seems rather sexiest to me. Where's a Bourbon soaked cake to start my day?) We gave it a try the next morning. Again, simple, yet comforting. The wine list was big, impressive, and pricey. We ordered the Claude Dugat 2009 red burgundy which was one of the cheap bottles at $120. Yes, it was good, but Jardiniere had the same bottle for $100. With their near perfect Zagat score, Michelin star, early reservations, and upscale price, I'd expect some added touches and put Danko at a higher standard. They scored points by letting us see the food menu before placing a cocktail, taking overcoats, offering to call a taxi, and, of course, the beautifully wrapped take-home cake. But they still fell short. Other niceties could have been clearing on the correct side of the diner, servers stepping aside when diners walk through the room, replacing obviously dirty napkins for diners who left the table, using a black for those dressed in black instead of a white napkin, and relief from the tightly packed tables (where I heard the neighboring diner slurp his food like a dog). Zagat says "jacket suggested", but it should have said "jacket ignored" as the majority of men were only in shirts on a windy day that only reached 67 degrees. I called the first morning when reservations become available and all time slots were open. So if you plan two months ahead, then there should be no problems getting a table.

Eating at Gary Danko is definitely an experience. It reminded me of the privilege I have to access, afford, and experience such food. The portions were extremely generous and the service was top notch. I almost cried when I took a bite of my chocolate souffle, it was so delicious. I think my friends would agree, the dessert was the best part! Had 5 courses, but really only needed 3. I recommend the ahi, pork belly with roast pork loin, and of course the souffle. The lobster salad and scallops were also good.

While in San Francisco a few weeks ago I was lucky enough to enjoy dinner at Restaurant Gary Danko, near Fisherman's Wharf. As usual, I was early for my dinner reservation, but the woman who greeted me was more than happy to show me to my table and to welcome me to Gary Danko. Upon stepping past the hostess desk my new shoes disagreed with the surface and I bit the dust. Hard. Now, after busting one's behind just before having a solo meal in a world-renowned restaurant it could be difficult to enjoy the meal or to swallow pride and laugh it off. Luckily, I am accustomed to finding humor in myself and managed to joke about it with the team for the rest of the evening. The entire crew was extremely apologetic and expressed their concern for me after my dramatic fall; they were so kind that they even saved me the hassle of picking out a glass of wine by presenting to me a complimentary sparkling rosÃ©. After making my selections for the 5-course menu, a tiny amuse bouche of seared beef over a noodle salad landed on my charger and I began to relax. Next, the perfect accompaniment to my bubbles arrived in the form of a perfectly buckwheat blini topped with caviar (a personal favorite) and thinly-sliced salmon; yet another impressive amuse bouche from Gary Danko. In addition, the sommelier who helped me throughout the evening brought to me a half-pour of Roederer L'Ermitage 2003 after I inquired into it while considering my own selection for the night. I was totally sold on every aspect of Gary Danko before a full course was even placed in front of me. For my first course I chose the soon-to-be-banned foie gras. The exterior was impeccably seared to create perfect caramelization and the center was warm and palate-coating while the reduction served to cut the fat and to give the plate finesse. This course showcased the foie gras as the star of the event and, given the state of California law, I am glad I was able to try this before Gary Danko's Chefs must remove it from the menu. My next selection was another one from the "Appetizers" category of the menu and focused on a large, crispy farm egg that had been breaded and deep-fried before being placed atop a creamy pool of white polenta with Royal Trumpet mushrooms, frisÃ©e, pancetta and uniformly crunchy croutons. As my fork pierced the softly-cooked egg the velvety yolk spilled into the creamy polenta and slowly saturated the croutons with eggy goodness. Egg dishes such as these are the epitome of the marriage of culinary opulence and classic simplicity; while the dish is far from simple, it combines comforting flavors and ingredients with artistic flair that brings out the best of each component. For my two seafood courses I welcomed the advice of my server and opted for seared scallops as well as Striped Bass with Speck. The scallops were cooked perfectly with the core remaining slightly cool to the touch. To highlight the flavors of springtime, the diver scallops were served with a refreshing asparagus-pea purÃ©e and sweet peas sitting atop glistening pools of Sauce MarÃ©chal. The next recommendation arrived in the form of Sea Bass with Speck. Imagine the smokiness of bacon with slow-aged Prosciutto. Speck comes from the hind leg of the hog and is cured in salt and spices before being rested, cold-smoked and aged. The Bass absorbed the fat and flavor of the speck while the brief cooking time kept the fish moist and tender. In a supporting role was a harmonious symphony of Stinging Nettle gnocchi, Morel mushrooms, asparagus, capers and Meyer lemon... wow! The contrasting and complimentary textures were amazing even without the beautiful combination of flavors that this plate brought so lovingly together. While I am not a cake person, I took my waiter's advice and selected the Louisiana Butter Cake for dessert. However, instead of being presented with the sweet that I expected, I was approached with two unexpected treats; the cheese cart and a congratulatory dessert. Everything was amazing! A couple of plates later... the Louisiana-inspired dessert was more like a sweetly-saturated bread pudding and was beyond satisfying. The combination of cake with caramelized apples, Huckleberry sauce and vanilla bean ice cream made this a noteworthy course. Finally, I was presented with an assortment of petit fours including pÃ¢tes de fruits, tarts and tiny cakes (just to name a few). Such an amazing finale. Before my departure I was given a beautifully-wrapped cake to enjoy for breakfast and was allowed a visit to the BOH; I was excited to say "thank you" and to see the infamous kitchen. The next time that I visit San Francisco I look forward to revisiting this culinary gem as my experience became better and better with each minute (after my entry) and the staff is one of the best I have encountered. To anyone visiting the area, make your reservation at Gary Danko. You will not regret the expense and will, hopefully, enjoy just as phenomenal of an experience as I did!

    This place gets 5 stars for the service and quality of the food-

    I was eager to dine here the evening we arrived in San Fran, it got so many reviews so I knew it had to be good-

    Upon arriving we were instantly seated and it wasn't a crappy table either,a table against a wall where both sat on the same side and viewed the dining room-

    When dining here you will not have the same waiter, everyone takes their turn to provide you what you need, from drinks to food-

    We were brought our bottled water and then the wine sommelier provided us with some wines to consider-He was very knowledgeable and we both decided on our selection-While we waited for our wine a person brought over a broth, in a very small bowl-It had maybe 2 full spoon fulls worth of liquid, it was a ginger/soy type broth-It was good but it made me ready to order-

    We were given bread and then our order was taken-With my selection I got the cheese, so the cheese cart was later wheeled over to me and I was presented with every cheese (at least 20) and the information behind it-You get 4 selections and the ones I did select were dead on with how they were described-

    It was fun to watch the staff serve each table and how they interacted with the guest, everyone was treated the same and each presentation was 100%, no slacking-
    It was impressive b/c everyone did different roles, so everyone had to know wines, cheeses, make the flambe etc.

    I ordered the roast lobster and my boyfriend ordered steak, we were both happy with what we ordered and had no complaints-

    I accidentally messed up and ordered the wrong dessert, the creme brulee when what I really wanted was the souffle so I was a little bummed by that but it was my own fault-My boyfriend devoured his so I know it was good-It was hard to watch as the server poured the white cream waterfall over his souffle then the milk chocolate waterfall...I sat and looked so sad probably watching this take place as I had to eat my brulee-Mine wasn't bad but it was zero chocolate and I didn't get magnificent waterfalls poured over the glorious dessert-My creme brulee had 3 flavors; basil, bourbon and lemon-Oddly enough I liked the basil one the best, lemon was a no-no and the bourbon was strong, good but just not for me-

    After we were done the hostess asked if would need a cab, which was awesome to have a restaurant provide that service-We said yes and while waiting to pay we were informed by the same hostess that our cab was in front waiting for us-Before we left we were given a plate of mini desserts and a wrapped banana cream bread for the next morning-We were stuffed so we took the mini desserts to go, which was given to us on our way out wrapped up nicely-

    In all it was a great experience, I thank everyone for being so nice to us and treating us so well-

    7/10/2012

    If it weren't for the desserts, Danko would be a highly disappointing 3-star flop. If they had a dessert tasting like at Providence in Los Angeles, I'm all in. I could then skip dinner and just have dessert.

    The amuse of merguez lamb sausage with cous cous was average. It was a questionable choice to open the evening with a spicy merguez.

    The deep fried egg appetizer with white polenta, king trumpet mushrooms, croutons, chives, and frissee was a dish that inspired breakfast. The eggs were perfectly cooked and burst with egg yolk when pierced. This was the only savory dish that I enjoyed, but the kitchen let an herb stem in the food slip though.

    Another starter, the pistachio coated sweetbreads with potato puree, roasted cauliflower, and mache was unbalanced. The cauliflower and sweetbreads were a double-whammy of pungent items. The pistachio crust didn't create a flavorful or crunchy exterior. The sweetbreads were laced with connective membrane that was unattractive. Like the errant stem, this was another sign the kitchen is not paying attention to details

    For mains, the lemon pepper duck breast was nicely cooked, but lacked much flavor. The duck & potato hash, shaped into a round, arrived cold and lacked fun potato starchiness. The outer leaf of the cabbage was stiff instead of tender and should have been peeled off before serving. The parsnip and carrot was an afterthought that "seemed" like a standard garnish that is put on all plates.

    Another entrÃ©e was the branzini with fennel and potato puree, orange segments, and saffron-infused orange sauce. The branzini was well cooked but overly mild. The concept of the dish sounds inventive, but ended up tasting conventional.

    Now for the good part - the desserts. Thankfully, we ordered two desserts instead of sharing one. I had the warm Louisiana butter cake with apples, berries, and lemon honey. It was inviting with an ideal balance between sugary, rich, and fruity. The ice cream macaroon sandwiches came in three flavors - pecan, raspberry, and pineapple. They had a good balance between the sweet from the ice cream and the bitter from the egg white. Both desserts weren't fancy and stylish, but ultimately very satisfying. The petit fours were nine tiny cookies that were ideal nibbles with appealingly conservative flavors. Female diners were given a parting gift of pineapple and vanilla white breakfast cake. (Kinda seems rather sexiest to me. Where's a Bourbon soaked cake to start my day?) We gave it a try the next morning. Again, simple, yet comforting.

    The wine list was big, impressive, and pricey. We ordered the Claude Dugat 2009 red burgundy which was one of the cheap bottles at $120. Yes, it was good, but Jardiniere had the same bottle for $100.

    With their near perfect Zagat score, Michelin star, early reservations, and upscale price, I'd expect some added touches and put Danko at a higher standard. They scored points by letting us see the food menu before placing a cocktail, taking overcoats, offering to call a taxi, and, of course, the beautifully wrapped take-home cake. But they still fell short. Other niceties could have been clearing on the correct side of the diner, servers stepping aside when diners walk through the room, replacing obviously dirty napkins for diners who left the table, using a black for those dressed in black instead of a white napkin, and relief from the tightly packed tables (where I heard the neighboring diner slurp his food like a dog).

    Zagat says "jacket suggested", but it should have said "jacket ignored" as the majority of men were only in shirts on a windy day that only reached 67 degrees.

    I called the first morning when reservations become available and all time slots were open. So if you plan two months ahead, then there should be no problems getting a table.

    While in San Francisco a few weeks ago I was lucky enough to enjoy dinner at Restaurant Gary Danko, near Fisherman's Wharf. As usual, I was early for my dinner reservation, but the woman who greeted me was more than happy to show me to my table and to welcome me to Gary Danko. Upon stepping past the hostess desk my new shoes disagreed with the surface and I bit the dust. Hard. Now, after busting one's behind just before having a solo meal in a world-renowned restaurant it could be difficult to enjoy the meal or to swallow pride and laugh it off. Luckily, I am accustomed to finding humor in myself and managed to joke about it with the team for the rest of the evening. The entire crew was extremely apologetic and expressed their concern for me after my dramatic fall; they were so kind that they even saved me the hassle of picking out a glass of wine by presenting to me a complimentary sparkling rosÃ©.

    After making my selections for the 5-course menu, a tiny amuse bouche of seared beef over a noodle salad landed on my charger and I began to relax. Next, the perfect accompaniment to my bubbles arrived in the form of a perfectly buckwheat blini topped with caviar (a personal favorite) and thinly-sliced salmon; yet another impressive amuse bouche from Gary Danko. In addition, the sommelier who helped me throughout the evening brought to me a half-pour of Roederer L'Ermitage 2003 after I inquired into it while considering my own selection for the night. I was totally sold on every aspect of Gary Danko before a full course was even placed in front of me.

    For my first course I chose the soon-to-be-banned foie gras. The exterior was impeccably seared to create perfect caramelization and the center was warm and palate-coating while the reduction served to cut the fat and to give the plate finesse. This course showcased the foie gras as the star of the event and, given the state of California law, I am glad I was able to try this before Gary Danko's Chefs must remove it from the menu. My next selection was another one from the "Appetizers" category of the menu and focused on a large, crispy farm egg that had been breaded and deep-fried before being placed atop a creamy pool of white polenta with Royal Trumpet mushrooms, frisÃ©e, pancetta and uniformly crunchy croutons. As my fork pierced the softly-cooked egg the velvety yolk spilled into the creamy polenta and slowly saturated the croutons with eggy goodness. Egg dishes such as these are the epitome of the marriage of culinary opulence and classic simplicity; while the dish is far from simple, it combines comforting flavors and ingredients with artistic flair that brings out the best of each component.

    For my two seafood courses I welcomed the advice of my server and opted for seared scallops as well as Striped Bass with Speck. The scallops were cooked perfectly with the core remaining slightly cool to the touch. To highlight the flavors of springtime, the diver scallops were served with a refreshing asparagus-pea purÃ©e and sweet peas sitting atop glistening pools of Sauce MarÃ©chal. The next recommendation arrived in the form of Sea Bass with Speck. Imagine the smokiness of bacon with slow-aged Prosciutto. Speck comes from the hind leg of the hog and is cured in salt and spices before being rested, cold-smoked and aged. The Bass absorbed the fat and flavor of the speck while the brief cooking time kept the fish moist and tender. In a supporting role was a harmonious symphony of Stinging Nettle gnocchi, Morel mushrooms, asparagus, capers and Meyer lemon... wow! The contrasting and complimentary textures were amazing even without the beautiful combination of flavors that this plate brought so lovingly together.

    While I am not a cake person, I took my waiter's advice and selected the Louisiana Butter Cake for dessert. However, instead of being presented with the sweet that I expected, I was approached with two unexpected treats; the cheese cart and a congratulatory dessert. Everything was amazing! A couple of plates later... the Louisiana-inspired dessert was more like a sweetly-saturated bread pudding and was beyond satisfying. The combination of cake with caramelized apples, Huckleberry sauce and vanilla bean ice cream made this a noteworthy course. Finally, I was presented with an assortment of petit fours including pÃ¢tes de fruits, tarts and tiny cakes (just to name a few). Such an amazing finale.

    Before my departure I was given a beautifully-wrapped cake to enjoy for breakfast and was allowed a visit to the BOH; I was excited to say "thank you" and to see the infamous kitchen. The next time that I visit San Francisco I look forward to revisiting this culinary gem as my experience became better and better with each minute (after my entry) and the staff is one of the best I have encountered. To anyone visiting the area, make your reservation at Gary Danko. You will not regret the expense and will, hopefully, enjoy just as phenomenal of an experience as I did!

    12/7/2012

    1 check-in

    Gary Danko, I wish I could give you 3 more stars to make it a total of eight lucky stars!!

    Seriously, what a lucky treat it was to dine here. Even the boyfriend was impressed and he's not easily impressed by fine dining when he thinks he can pay less to get more.

    Service was warm, inviting and impeccable. I knew we were in a nice place since everyone was dressed nicely, but the service here made you feel like you were at a warm gathering with old friends. No hoity toity crap going on here.

    Food was generous and the menu made it easy to order. When you open the menu, the left side is the a la carte menu and the right side is the tasting menu. You can choose from 3, 4 or 5 course tastings. Every item on the tasting menu can be found on the a la carte menu, but not vice versa. What I loved about the tasting menu was you could order however you want. So if you want 3 tastings and you want all desserts, then go for it.

    Some of the dishes we loved and savored every bit were:
    -Lobster risotto
    -Pickled beet salad
    -Pork tenderloin medium rare

    The dish I was not crazy about:
    -Chocolate souffle. It was not chocolatey or hot enough for me. I think it really lacked oomph that all the other dishes had.

    Price-wise, Gary is a generous man. I think he can charge more if he wanted to, but I really appreciate that he makes the menu affordable and easy to order so that he can share the food of love with his patrons. Seriously, I mean that. What kinda Michelin-star restaurant only charges $3.75 for coffee + unlimited refills??

    Definitely worth the experience. Probably one of the most memorable dining experiences we've ever had.
